00:00:00.766 --> 00:00:03.800
- [Voiceover] Let's explore
the infinite series.

00:00:04.433 --> 00:00:06.134
We're going to start at n equals one,

00:00:06.368 --> 00:00:10.600
and go to infinity of
negative one to the n plus one

00:00:10.966 --> 00:00:14.166
over n squared, which is
going to be equal to ...

00:00:14.166 --> 00:00:16.801
Let's see, when n is one,
this is going to be positive.

00:00:16.833 --> 00:00:18.167
It's going to be one.

00:00:18.167 --> 00:00:20.967
This, you go minus one over two squares,

00:00:20.967 --> 00:00:22.200
is minus 1/4

00:00:22.566 --> 00:00:24.200
plus 1/9

00:00:24.633 --> 00:00:28.333
minus 1/16

00:00:28.637 --> 00:00:30.434
plus 1/25 ...

00:00:30.434 --> 00:00:32.100
I'm actually going to go pretty far ...

00:00:32.100 --> 00:00:34.470
Minus 1/36,

00:00:34.833 --> 00:00:37.668
plus 1/49,

00:00:37.966 --> 00:00:40.269
minus 1/64.

00:00:41.101 --> 00:00:42.877
Yeah, that's pretty good.

00:00:42.877 --> 00:00:43.434
I'll stop there.

00:00:43.434 --> 00:00:45.633
Of course, we keep going on and on and on,

00:00:45.633 --> 00:00:48.105
and it's an alternating
series, plus, minus,

00:00:48.105 --> 00:00:50.666
just keeps going on and
on and on and on forever.

00:00:51.233 --> 00:00:53.366
Now, we know from previous tests,

00:00:53.366 --> 00:00:55.500
in fact, the alternating series test,

00:00:55.500 --> 00:00:57.104
that this satisfies the constraints

00:00:57.104 --> 00:00:59.766
of the alternating series test,

00:00:59.766 --> 00:01:01.466
and we're able to show that it converges.

00:01:01.900 --> 00:01:03.900
What we're doing now is,
actually trying to estimate

00:01:03.900 --> 00:01:05.533
what things converge to.

00:01:08.334 --> 00:01:11.466
We want to estimate
what this value, S, is.

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:12.766
We're going to do that by doing

00:01:12.766 --> 00:01:15.233
a finite number of calculations,

00:01:15.233 --> 00:01:18.000
by not having to add this
entire thing together.

00:01:18.701 --> 00:01:20.433
Let's estimate it by taking, let's say,

00:01:20.433 --> 00:01:22.533
the partial sum of the first four terms.

00:01:23.234 --> 00:01:26.133
Let's take these four
terms right over here.

00:01:26.566 --> 00:01:29.933
Let's call that, that's
going to be S sub four.

00:01:30.336 --> 00:01:31.700
Then you're going to have a remainder,

00:01:31.700 --> 00:01:33.000
which is going to be everything else.

00:01:33.367 --> 00:01:34.570
All of this other stuff,

00:01:34.570 --> 00:01:36.133
I don't want even the brackets to end.

00:01:36.166 --> 00:01:38.133
That's going to be your remainder,

00:01:38.236 --> 00:01:42.000
the remainder, to get
to your actually sum,

00:01:42.300 --> 00:01:43.433
or whatever's left over

00:01:43.433 --> 00:01:45.300
when you just take the first four terms.

00:01:45.300 --> 00:01:48.269
This is from the fifth term
all the way to infinity.

00:01:48.634 --> 00:01:49.766
We've seen this before.

00:01:49.766 --> 00:01:52.466
The actual sum is going to
be equal to this partial sum

00:01:52.700 --> 00:01:54.466
plus this remainder.

00:01:54.966 --> 00:01:56.534
Well, we can calculate this.

00:01:56.700 --> 00:01:58.033
This is going to be, let's see ...

00:01:58.033 --> 00:01:59.933
Common denominator here,

00:02:00.034 --> 00:02:02.866
see, nine times 16 is 144.

00:02:02.900 --> 00:02:05.666
That's going to be 144,

00:02:05.966 --> 00:02:10.966
and then that's going
to be 144 minus 36/144,

00:02:11.771 --> 00:02:16.666
plus 16/144, minus 9/144.

00:02:16.700 --> 00:02:20.700
Let's see, that is 144,
negative 36 plus 16

00:02:20.700 --> 00:02:25.666
is minus 20, so it's
124 minus nine, is 115.

00:02:26.166 --> 00:02:28.100
This is all going to be

00:02:28.100 --> 00:02:31.966
equal to 115/144.

00:02:31.966 --> 00:02:33.469
I didn't even need a
calculator to figure that out.

00:02:33.700 --> 00:02:35.666
Plus some remainder.

00:02:36.366 --> 00:02:38.333
Plus some remainder.

00:02:39.500 --> 00:02:42.200
So, if we could figure out
some bounds on this remainder,

00:02:42.433 --> 00:02:47.433
we will figure out the
bounds on our actual sum.

00:02:48.900 --> 00:02:49.900
We'll be able to figure out,

00:02:49.900 --> 00:02:53.133
"Well, how far is this away
from this right over here?"

00:02:53.833 --> 00:02:55.833
There's two ways to think about it.

00:02:55.833 --> 00:02:57.733
Let's look at it.

00:02:57.900 --> 00:03:00.567
The first thing I want to see is,

00:03:00.567 --> 00:03:03.433
I want to show you that this
